{"title_page": "Inholland University of Applied Sciences", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Inholland University of Applied Sciences\n| native_name = Hogeschool Inholland\n| image = [[File:Short logo.png|Short logo]]\n| caption = Inholland University of Applied Sciences official logo\n| motto = Leren = durven\n| mottoeng = Learning = daring\n| established = 1 September 2002\n| type = University of Applied Sciences\n| chairperson = Jet de Ranitz\n| students = 37,000; 6000 international students\n| city = [[The Hague]], [[Amsterdam]], [[Haarlem]], [[Alkmaar]], [[Delft]], [[Diemen]], [[Dordrecht]], [[Rotterdam]]\n| province = [[South Holland]]\n| country = [[Netherlands]]\n| campus = Multiple campuses\n| language = ISO 639-1\n| colours = {{color box|#E10075}} [[Magenta]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.inholland.nl/}}\n}}\n\n'''Inholland University of Applied Sciences''' is a [[university]] of applied sciences with its campuses located in 8 different cities<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/locaties/|title=Locaties - Hogeschool Inholland - Hbo-opleidingen|website=www.inholland.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> placed throughout the western [[Netherlands]] with an education campus in every main city of the [[Randstad]] \u2013 the country\u2019s economic, political and cultural substantiation. With over 37,000 students from more than 100 countries, the university follows the applied sciences mode of education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/over-inholland/|title=Over Inholland - Hogeschool Inholland|website=www.inholland.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n[[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor's degrees]] at Inholland University of Applied Sciences demand three or four years of full-time study and require 240 European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credits. One [[ECTS grading scale|ECTS]] credit represents 28 hours of full-time study and the study/workload for one academic year accounts for 60 credits.The Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders ([[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders|NVAO]]) approves study programs offered by [[Dutch universities]]. All international bachelor's programs offered by Inholland University of Applied Sciences are recognised by [[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders|NVAO]].\n\nThe [[degree programs]] of Inholland University of Applied Sciences are divided into faculties. There are 75 Bachelor's programs provided by Inholland. The international bachelor's programs come under the faculties of Creative Business and Engineering, Design and Computing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/opleidingen-v2/#/|title=- Hbo-opleidingen Hogeschool Inholland|website=www.inholland.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Locations ==\nInholland University has campuses in the following cities:\n* [[Alkmaar]]\n* [[Amsterdam]]\n* [[Delft]]\n* [[The Hague]]\n* [[Diemen]]\n* [[Dordrecht]]\n* [[Haarlem]]\n* [[Rotterdam]]\n\n[[File:Inholland-building.jpg|alt=|thumb|250x250px|Inholland Campus Rotterdam]]\n\n== Faculties ==\n'''Agri, Food & Life Sciences''' \n\nLocations: [[Amsterdam]] and [[Delft]] \n\n'''Business, Finance & Law''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \u00a0\n\n'''Creative Business''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \u00a0\n\n'''Health, Sport and Welfare''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Amsterdam]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \n\n'''Education & Innovation''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]], [[Rotterdam]] and [[Dordrecht]] \u00a0\n\n'''Engineering, Design and Computing'''\n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[Delft]] and [[Haarlem]] \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|en}} [https://www.inholland.nl/inhollandcom/ Official website]\n\n{{Dutch Vocational Universities}}\n\n{{coord missing|Netherlands}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vocational universities in the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Inholland University of Applied Sciences\n| native_name = Hogeschool Inholland\n| image = [[File:Short logo.png|Short logo]]\n| caption = Inholland University of Applied Sciences official logo\n| motto = Leren = durven\n| mottoeng = Learning = daring\n| established = 1 September 2002\n| type = University of Applied Sciences\n| chairperson = Jet de Ranitz\n| students = 28,000\n| city = [[The Hague]], [[Amsterdam]], [[Haarlem]], [[Alkmaar]], [[Delft]], [[Diemen]], [[Dordrecht]], [[Rotterdam]]\n| province = [[South Holland]]\n| country = [[Netherlands]]\n| campus = Multiple campuses\n| language = ISO 639-1\n| colours = {{color box|#E10075}} [[Magenta]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.inholland.nl/}}\n}}\n\n'''Inholland University of Applied Sciences''' is a [[university]] of applied sciences with its campuses located in 8 different cities placed throughout the western [[Netherlands]] with an education campus in every main city of the [[Randstad]] \u2013 the country\u2019s economic, political and cultural substantiation. With over 28,000 students from more than 100 countries, the university follows the applied sciences mode of education. \n\n[[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor's degrees]] at Inholland University of Applied Sciences demand three or four years of full-time study and require 240 European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credits. One [[ECTS grading scale|ECTS]] credit represents 28 hours of full-time study and the study/workload for one academic year accounts for 60 credits.The Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders ([[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders|NVAO]]) approves study programs offered by [[Dutch universities]]. All international bachelor's programs offered by Inholland University of Applied Sciences are recognised by [[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders|NVAO]].\n\nThe [[degree programs]] of Inholland University of Applied Sciences are divided into faculties. There are 75 Bachelor's programs provided by Inholland. The international bachelor's programs come under the faculties of Creative Business and Engineering, Design and Computing. \u00a0\n\n== Locations ==\nInholland University has campuses in the following cities:\n* [[Alkmaar]]\n* [[Amsterdam]]\n* [[Delft]]\n* [[The Hague]]\n* [[Diemen]]\n* [[Dordrecht]]\n* [[Haarlem]]\n* [[Rotterdam]]\n\n[[File:Inholland-building.jpg|alt=|thumb|250x250px|Inholland Campus Rotterdam]]\n\n== Faculties ==\n'''Agri, Food & Life Sciences''' \n\nLocations: [[Amsterdam]] and [[Delft]] \n\n'''Business, Finance & Law''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \u00a0\n\n'''Creative Business''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \u00a0\n\n'''Health, Sport and Welfare''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Amsterdam]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \n\n'''Education & Innovation''' \n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]], [[Rotterdam]] and [[Dordrecht]] \u00a0\n\n'''Engineering, Design and Computing'''\n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[Delft]] and [[Haarlem]] \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|en}} [https://www.inholland.nl/inhollandcom/ Official website]\n\n{{Dutch Vocational Universities}}\n\n{{coord missing|Netherlands}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vocational universities in the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Adrianvanrein", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inholland_University_of_Applied_Sciences"}
{"title_page": "EScholar", "text_new": "{{lowercase title}}\n'''eScholar''' is a software company that provides software and services used by educators for student record management and [[Career management|career planning]]. eScholar manages data on more than 20 million students across the [[United States]] with its software.<ref name=\":2\" />{{Infobox company\n| name                = eScholar\n| industry            = Computer software\n| founded             = 1997\n| key_people          = Shawn Bay ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| website             = https://www.escholar.com\n}}\n\n== History ==\neScholar was founded in 1997 by Shawn Bay.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://edgrowth.com/index.php/2012/01/19/education-growth-partners-completes-investment-in-escholar-llc/|title=Education Growth Partners Completes Investment in eScholar LLC|date=2012-01-19|website=Education Growth Partners|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Prior to eScholar, Bay was a marketing analyst at [[Procter & Gamble]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Berger|first=Leslie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/13/education/blackboard-business-intelligence-insights-from-the-data-pile.html|title=BLACKBOARD; Business Intelligence: Insights From the Data Pile|date=2002-01-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> eScholar is based in [[White Plains, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westchestermagazine.com/publications/heres-how-westchester-turns-tech-into-revenue/|title=Here's How Westchester Turns Tech Into Revenue|date=2018-08-07|website=Westchester Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[Plainfield Public School District]] in [[New Jersey]], [[United States|U.S.]] began using a data warehouse and analysis solution provided by eScholar.<ref name=\":1\" /> Between 2000 and 2002, eScholar grew from 10 to more than 600 school districts as clients.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2004, the [[Johns Hopkins University]] Center for Research on the Education of Students Placed At Risk (CRESPAR) published a report considering the implications of the collection and use of student data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED489950|title=Software Enabling School Improvement through Analysis of Student Data|last=Wayman|first=Jeffrey C.|last2=Stringfield|first2=Sam|date=2004-01-01|website=|publisher=Center for Research on the Education of Students Placed at Risk (CRESPAR), Johns Hopkins University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Yakimowski|first3=Mary}}</ref> This report explored the use of eScholar's data warehouse tool and other student data tooling.\n\nIn 2006, the [[Illinois State Board of Education]] selected eScholar as a subcontractor to author a feasibility study and functional requirements analysis for a [[data warehouse]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isbe.net/Documents/feasibility_study.pdf|title=Feasibility Study and Functional Requirements Analysis for Development and Implementation of the ISBE Data Warehouse|last=|first=|date=2006-03-06|website=Illinois State Board of Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> As of this same year, the company had built data warehouses in at least 20 states.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dillon|first=Sam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/15/education/15computers.html|title=States Struggle to Computerize School Records|date=2006-05-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, eScholar received media attention related to its [[Information privacy|data privacy]] practices.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/05/data-mining-your-children-106676.html|title=The big biz of spying on little kids|last=Simon|first=Stephanie|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Investor|Investors]] in eScholar include Education Growth Partners.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejournal.com/articles/2017/03/20/escholar-mytrack-expands-granular-access-to-education-data.aspx|title=eScholar myTrack Expands Granular Access to Education Data -|last=Schaffhauser|first=By Dian|last2=03/20/17|website=THE Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Educational software]]\n[[Category:Educational software companies]]\n", "text_old": "'''eScholar''' is a software company that provides software and services used by educators for student record management and [[Career management|career planning]]. eScholar manages data on more than 20 million students across the [[United States]] with its software.<ref name=\":2\" />{{Infobox company\n| name                = eScholar\n| industry            = Computer software\n| founded             = 1997\n| key_people          = Shawn Bay ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| website             = https://www.escholar.com\n}}\n\n== History ==\neScholar was founded in 1997 by Shawn Bay.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://edgrowth.com/index.php/2012/01/19/education-growth-partners-completes-investment-in-escholar-llc/|title=Education Growth Partners Completes Investment in eScholar LLC|date=2012-01-19|website=Education Growth Partners|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Prior to eScholar, Bay was a marketing analyst at [[Procter & Gamble]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Berger|first=Leslie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/13/education/blackboard-business-intelligence-insights-from-the-data-pile.html|title=BLACKBOARD; Business Intelligence: Insights From the Data Pile|date=2002-01-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> eScholar is based in [[White Plains, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westchestermagazine.com/publications/heres-how-westchester-turns-tech-into-revenue/|title=Here's How Westchester Turns Tech Into Revenue|date=2018-08-07|website=Westchester Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[Plainfield Public School District]] in [[New Jersey]], [[United States|U.S.]] began using a data warehouse and analysis solution provided by eScholar.<ref name=\":1\" /> Between 2000 and 2002, eScholar grew from 10 to more than 600 school districts as clients.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2004, the [[Johns Hopkins University]] Center for Research on the Education of Students Placed At Risk (CRESPAR) published a report considering the implications of the collection and use of student data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED489950|title=Software Enabling School Improvement through Analysis of Student Data|last=Wayman|first=Jeffrey C.|last2=Stringfield|first2=Sam|date=2004-01-01|website=|publisher=Center for Research on the Education of Students Placed at Risk (CRESPAR), Johns Hopkins University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Yakimowski|first3=Mary}}</ref> This report explored the use of eScholar's data warehouse tool and other student data tooling.\n\nIn 2006, the [[Illinois State Board of Education]] selected eScholar as a subcontractor to author a feasibility study and functional requirements analysis for a [[data warehouse]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isbe.net/Documents/feasibility_study.pdf|title=Feasibility Study and Functional Requirements Analysis for Development and Implementation of the ISBE Data Warehouse|last=|first=|date=2006-03-06|website=Illinois State Board of Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> As of this same year, the company had built data warehouses in at least 20 states.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dillon|first=Sam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/15/education/15computers.html|title=States Struggle to Computerize School Records|date=2006-05-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, eScholar received media attention related to its [[Information privacy|data privacy]] practices.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/05/data-mining-your-children-106676.html|title=The big biz of spying on little kids|last=Simon|first=Stephanie|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Investor|Investors]] in eScholar include Education Growth Partners.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejournal.com/articles/2017/03/20/escholar-mytrack-expands-granular-access-to-education-data.aspx|title=eScholar myTrack Expands Granular Access to Education Data -|last=Schaffhauser|first=By Dian|last2=03/20/17|website=THE Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Educational software]]\n[[Category:Educational software companies]]\n", "name_user": "EdTechUser", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adjust page title to lowercase", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EScholar"}
{"title_page": "Jeannie Seely (1990 album)", "text_new": "{{about|the 1990 eponymous album|the 1969 eponymous album|Jeannie Seely (1969 album)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Jeannie Seely\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| cover      = Jeannie Seely--1990 albums.jpg\n| released   = {{start date|1990}}\n| recorded   = 1989\u20131990\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (Cassette Liner Notes & Album Information) |journal=Faux Paw Productions/Shadpoke Records |date=1990}}</ref>\n| length     =\n| label      = {{hlist|Faux Paw|Shadpoke}}\n| producer   = Jeannie Seely\n| prev_title = [[Greatest Hits (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| prev_year  = 1982\n| next_title = [[Number One Christmas]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n'''''Jeannie Seely''''' is a studio album by American [[country music]] artist [[Jeannie Seely]]. The album was released in 1990 on Faux Paw Productions and Shadpoke Records. The album was produced by Seely as well. The project was Seely's first studio album in eight years and second eponymous album to be released. It would be one of several studio records she would record during the 1990s.\n\n==Background and release==\n''Jeannie Seely'' was recorded between 1989 and 1990. It was the first album to be produced by Seely herself. Some of her future releases would also be self-produced.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The album consisted of ten tracks.<ref name=\"Discogs\">{{cite web |title=''Jeannie Seely'' -- Jeannie Seely (1990, Cassette) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Jeannie-Seely/release/12067980 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> Among the album's tracks was a re-recording of \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\", Seely's signature song. It was the second time that Seely had re-recorded the tune. Another track on the album was a cover version of [[Michael Bolton]]'s hit \"[[When I'm Back on My Feet Again]]\". Another song on the album, \"Healing Hands of Time\", was composed by [[Willie Nelson]].<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The project also included six tracks that were written or co-written by Seely.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n''Jeannie Seely'' was released in 1990 on Faux Paw Productions and Shadpoke Productions. These two companies had been founded by Seely.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The album was released as a [[audio cassette|cassette]] with five songs on each side of the device.<ref name=\"Discogs\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely Discography |url=http://jeannieseely.com/discography.cfm |website=Jeannie Seely.com |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> The album marked Seely's first studio release in eight years and second eponymous album to be issued. The album did not produce any known singles nor did it reach any peak positions on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' music charts.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n| title1          = [[Don't Touch Me]] \n| note1           = {{small|re-recording}}\n| writer1         = [[Hank Cochran]]\n| title2          = If It Was That Easy\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Jeannie Seely|John Virgin}}\n| title3          = Healing Hands of Time\n| writer3         = [[Willie Nelson]]\n| title4          = Why Doesn't He Leave Me Alone\n| writer4         = {{hlist|[[Dean Dillon]]|Seely}}\n| title5          = All Through Cryin'\n| writer5         = Seely\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two<ref name=\"Discogs\"/>\n| title1          = [[When I'm Back on My Feet Again]]\n| writer1         = [[Diane Warren]]\n| title2          = I'll Be Around\n| writer2         = Seely\n| title3          = Two Cheaters Loose\n| writer3         = Seely\n| title4          = One Step Away\n| writer4         = Seely\n| title5          = Every Now and Then\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Shayne Dolan|Rock Killough}}\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nAll credits are adapted from the [[liner notes]] of ''Jeannie Seely''.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n* Jeannie Seely \u2013 lead vocals, producer\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Region\n!scope=\"col\"| Date\n!scope=\"col\"| Format\n!scope=\"col\"| Label\n!scope=\"col\"| Ref.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United States\n| 1990\n| Cassette\n| {{hlist|Faux Paw Productions|Shadpoke Records}}\n| <ref name=\"Discogs\"/><ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n[[Category:1990 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jeannie Seely]]\n[[Category:Jeannie Seely albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 1990 eponymous album|the 1969 eponymous album|Jeannie Seely (1969 album)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Jeannie Seely\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| cover      = Jeannie Seely--1990 albums.jpg\n| released   = {{start date|1990}}\n| recorded   = 1989\u20131990\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (Cassette Liner Notes & Album Information) |journal=Faux Paw Productions/Shadpoke Records |date=1990}}</ref>\n| length     =\n| label      = {{hlist|Faux Paw|Shadpoke}}\n| producer   = Jeannie Seely\n| prev_title = [[Greatest Hits (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| prev_year  = 1982\n| next_title = [[Number One Christmas]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n'''''Jeannie Seely''''' is a studio album by American [[country music]] artist [[Jeannie Seely]]. The album was released in 1990 on Faux Paw Productions and Shadpoke Records. The album was produced by Seely as well. The project was Seely's first studio album in eight years and second eponymous album to be released. It would be one of several studio records she would record during the 1990s.\n\n==Background and release==\n''Jeannie Seely'' was recorded between 1989 and 1990. It was the first album to be produced by Seely herself. Some of her future releases would also be self-produced.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The album consisted of ten tracks.<ref name=\"Discogs\">{{cite web |title=''Jeannie Seely'' -- Jeannie Seely (1990, Cassette) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Jeannie-Seely/release/12067980 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> Among the album's tracks was a re-recording of \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\", Seely's signature song. It was the second time that Seely had re-recorded the tune. Another track on the album was a cover version of [[Michael Bolton]]'s hit \"[[When I'm Back on My Feet Again]]\". Another song on the album, \"Healing Hands of Time\", was composed by [[Willie Nelson]].<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The project also included six tracks that were written or co-written by Seely.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n''Jeannie Seely'' was released in 1990 on Faux Paw Productions and Shadpoke Productions. These two companies had been founded by Seely.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The album was released as a [[audio cassette|cassette]] with five songs on each side of the device.<ref name=\"Discogs\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely Discography |url=http://jeannieseely.com/discography.cfm |website=Jeannie Seely.com |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> The album marked Seely's first studio release in eight years and second eponymous album to be issued. The album did not produce any known singles nor did it reach any peak positions on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' music charts.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n| title1          = [[Don't Touch Me]] \n| note1           = re-recording\n| writer1         = [[Hank Cochran]]\n| title2          = If It Was That Easy\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Jeannie Seely|John Virgin}}\n| title3          = Healing Hands of Time\n| writer3         = [[Willie Nelson]]\n| title4          = Why Doesn't He Leave Me Alone\n| writer4         = {{hlist|[[Dean Dillon]]|Seely}}\n| title5          = All Through Cryin'\n| writer5         = Seely\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two<ref name=\"Discogs\"/>\n| title1          = [[When I'm Back on My Feet Again]]\n| writer1         = [[Diane Warren]]\n| title2          = I'll Be Around\n| writer2         = Seely\n| title3          = Two Cheaters Loose\n| writer3         = Seely\n| title4          = One Step Away\n| writer4         = Seely\n| title5          = Every Now and Then\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Shayne Dolan|Rock Killough}}\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nAll credits are adapted from the [[liner notes]] of ''Jeannie Seely''.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n* Jeannie Seely \u2013 lead vocals, producer\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Region\n!scope=\"col\"| Date\n!scope=\"col\"| Format\n!scope=\"col\"| Label\n!scope=\"col\"| Ref.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United States\n| 1990\n| Cassette\n| {{hlist|Faux Paw Productions|Shadpoke Records}}\n| <ref name=\"Discogs\"/><ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n[[Category:1990 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jeannie Seely]]\n[[Category:Jeannie Seely albums]]\n", "name_user": "ChrisTofu11961", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listing:added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeannie_Seely_(1990_album)"}
{"title_page": "St Ricarius Church, Aberford", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n| fullname             = Church of St Ricarius or St Riquier\n| image                = St Ricarius Nov 2016 (42).JPG\n| imagesize            = 200px\n| coordinates          = {{coord|53.828854|-1.343817|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| location             = [[Aberford]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| country              = [[England]]\n| denomination         = [[Church of England]]\n| status               = [[Parish Church]]\n| heritage designation = [[Grade II listed building]]\n| architect            = Anthony Salvin\n| completed date       = 1861\n| materials            = [[Magnesian Limestone|Magnesian limestone]]\n| province              = [[York]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Church of St Ricarius''', [[Aberford]], [[West Yorkshire]], England, is an active [[Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the archdeaconry of York and the [[Anglican ArchDiocese of York|Diocese of York]]. It is commonly stated that the dedication refers to the French saint [[Richarius|St Richarius or Riquier]] who is supposed to have visited Aberford in 630.<ref name=Mee>{{cite book |last=Mee |first=Arthur |year=1941 |title=The King's England: Yorkshire West Riding|url= |edition=1st|publisher=Hodder and Stoughton |location=London|page=17 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref><ref name=Armfield>{{cite book |last=Armfield |first=H. M. |year=2011 |title= A History of Aberford |url= |edition=2nd|publisher=available from St Ricarius Church, Aberford |location=Aberford|page=5 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>  However, the church itself has a stained glass window depicting \"Ricarius Rex 720\" (King Richard) the Saxon King also known as [[Richard the Pilgrim|St Richard the Pilgrim]].<ref name=LI>''Leeds Intelligencer'', Saturday 03 May 1862 p8: \"Aberford Church reopening and consecration\"</ref>\n[[File:St Ricarius Aberford West Yorks (107a).jpg|thumb|left|Ricarius Rex window]]\n\n==History==\n\nApart from the [[Norman architecture|Norman]] tower, one Norman window and a 13th-century window, the church is largely an 1861 rebuilding of a 12th-century church by [[Anthony Salvin]].<ref name=Mee/><ref name=Armfield18>{{cite book |last=Armfield |first=H. M. |year=2011 |title= A History of Aberford |url= |edition=2nd|publisher=available from St Ricarius Church, Aberford |location=|pages=18\u201319 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref><ref name=BLB>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101313204-parish-church-of-st-ricarius-or-st-riquier-aberford#.WPDkwpU2waJ|publisher=British Listed Buildings|title=Parish Church of St Ricarius or St Riquier|date=|accessdate=2017-04-14}}</ref> The church was listed as a grade II [[listed building]] on 3 February 1967.<ref name=BLB/>\n\n==Architectural style==\n===Exterior===\nThe church is of [[Magnesian Limestone|magnesian limestone]] with a slate roof. The west tower has a short octagonal spire and copies the style of the former tower: it has three stages with a rubble base and from there up is of squared masonry. The [[Belfry (architecture)|belfry]] has Normal-style round-headed belfry windows on all sides of the third stage and a clock face on the eastern side. There is a nave with both north and south aisles and a gabled porch to the south aisle. The church has a north vestry and a small chancel with south chapel. The chapel has a small priest's door and window.<ref name=BLB/>  The porch has a sundial dating from 1806.<ref name=Mee/>\n\n===Interior===\nThe church has four-bay arcades with double-chamfered arches and short cylindrical columns. The chancel arch has a 20th-century figurative painting. There is a two-bay arcade on either side of the chancel and on the north side a Norman lancet, perhaps relocated from the previous church. The church contains the anvil of blacksmith Samuel Hick, who is buried outside. There is an octagonal stone font with an ornate carved wooden cover.<ref name=BLB/>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:St Ricarius Nov 2016 (74).JPG|Interior\nFile:St Ricarius Aberford West Yorks (41).JPG|Carved wooden cover over the font\nFile:St Ricarius Church (69).JPG|Clock chamber\nFile:St Ricarius Nov 2016 (77).JPG|Font and cover\nFile:St Ricarius Aberford West Yorks (71).JPG|Sundial over porch\nFile:Choir at St Ricarius Aberford.jpg|The choir at the church in the early 20th century\n</gallery>\n\n==Market Cross==\n[[File:St. Ricarius Church, Aberford (22nd March 2014) 003.JPG|thumb|right|Market Cross at the church]]\nOutside the church's south gate is a former [[market cross]] thought to be of 17th-century origin which was relocated here in 1911. Like the church the cross is of magnesian limestone. The cross has two circular steps and a stone pedestal and octagonal plinth. There is a lettered brass plaque claiming the cross was removed during the plague in 1644 and restored and relocated to commemorate the coronation of [[King George V]] in 1911.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101135611-market-cross-beside-south-gate-to-church-of-st-ricarius-aberford#.WPDrWZU2waI|publisher=British Listed Buildings|title=Market Cross Beside South Gate to Church of St Ricarius|date=|accessdate=2017-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places of worship in the City of Leeds]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|St. Ricarius Church, Aberford}}\n*[https://www.achurchnearyou.com/aberford-st-ricarius/ St Ricarius' Church, Aberford]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aberford, St. Ricarius' Church}}\n[[Category:Churches in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Listed buildings in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Anglican Diocese of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Church of England church buildings in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed churches in West Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n| fullname             = Church of St Ricarius or St Riquier\n| image                = St Ricarius Nov 2016 (42).JPG\n| imagesize            = 200px\n| location             = [[Aberford]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| country              = [[England]]\n| denomination         = [[Church of England]]\n| status               = [[Parish Church]]\n| heritage designation = [[Grade II listed building]]\n| architect            = Anthony Salvin\n| completed date       = 1861\n| materials            = [[Magnesian Limestone|Magnesian limestone]]\n| province              = [[York]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Church of St Ricarius''', [[Aberford]], [[West Yorkshire]], England, is an active [[Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the archdeaconry of York and the [[Anglican ArchDiocese of York|Diocese of York]]. It is commonly stated that the dedication refers to the French saint [[Richarius|St Richarius or Riquier]] who is supposed to have visited Aberford in 630.<ref name=Mee>{{cite book |last=Mee |first=Arthur |year=1941 |title=The King's England: Yorkshire West Riding|url= |edition=1st|publisher=Hodder and Stoughton |location=London|page=17 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref><ref name=Armfield>{{cite book |last=Armfield |first=H. M. |year=2011 |title= A History of Aberford |url= |edition=2nd|publisher=available from St Ricarius Church, Aberford |location=Aberford|page=5 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>  However, the church itself has a stained glass window depicting \"Ricarius Rex 720\" (King Richard) the Saxon King also known as [[Richard the Pilgrim|St Richard the Pilgrim]].<ref name=LI>''Leeds Intelligencer'', Saturday 03 May 1862 p8: \"Aberford Church reopening and consecration\"</ref>\n[[File:St Ricarius Aberford West Yorks (107a).jpg|thumb|left|Ricarius Rex window]]\n\n==History==\n\nApart from the [[Norman architecture|Norman]] tower, one Norman window and a 13th-century window, the church is largely an 1861 rebuilding of a 12th-century church by [[Anthony Salvin]].<ref name=Mee/><ref name=Armfield18>{{cite book |last=Armfield |first=H. M. |year=2011 |title= A History of Aberford |url= |edition=2nd|publisher=available from St Ricarius Church, Aberford |location=|pages=18\u201319 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref><ref name=BLB>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101313204-parish-church-of-st-ricarius-or-st-riquier-aberford#.WPDkwpU2waJ|publisher=British Listed Buildings|title=Parish Church of St Ricarius or St Riquier|date=|accessdate=2017-04-14}}</ref> The church was listed as a grade II [[listed building]] on 3 February 1967.<ref name=BLB/>\n\n==Architectural style==\n===Exterior===\nThe church is of [[Magnesian Limestone|magnesian limestone]] with a slate roof. The west tower has a short octagonal spire and copies the style of the former tower: it has three stages with a rubble base and from there up is of squared masonry. The [[Belfry (architecture)|belfry]] has Normal-style round-headed belfry windows on all sides of the third stage and a clock face on the eastern side. There is a nave with both north and south aisles and a gabled porch to the south aisle. The church has a north vestry and a small chancel with south chapel. The chapel has a small priest's door and window.<ref name=BLB/>  The porch has a sundial dating from 1806.<ref name=Mee/>\n\n===Interior===\nThe church has four-bay arcades with double-chamfered arches and short cylindrical columns. The chancel arch has a 20th-century figurative painting. There is a two-bay arcade on either side of the chancel and on the north side a Norman lancet, perhaps relocated from the previous church. The church contains the anvil of blacksmith Samuel Hick, who is buried outside. There is an octagonal stone font with an ornate carved wooden cover.<ref name=BLB/>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:St Ricarius Nov 2016 (74).JPG|Interior\nFile:St Ricarius Aberford West Yorks (41).JPG|Carved wooden cover over the font\nFile:St Ricarius Church (69).JPG|Clock chamber\nFile:St Ricarius Nov 2016 (77).JPG|Font and cover\nFile:St Ricarius Aberford West Yorks (71).JPG|Sundial over porch\nFile:Choir at St Ricarius Aberford.jpg|The choir at the church in the early 20th century\n</gallery>\n\n==Market Cross==\n[[File:St. Ricarius Church, Aberford (22nd March 2014) 003.JPG|thumb|right|Market Cross at the church]]\nOutside the church's south gate is a former [[market cross]] thought to be of 17th-century origin which was relocated here in 1911. Like the church the cross is of magnesian limestone. The cross has two circular steps and a stone pedestal and octagonal plinth. There is a lettered brass plaque claiming the cross was removed during the plague in 1644 and restored and relocated to commemorate the coronation of [[King George V]] in 1911.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101135611-market-cross-beside-south-gate-to-church-of-st-ricarius-aberford#.WPDrWZU2waI|publisher=British Listed Buildings|title=Market Cross Beside South Gate to Church of St Ricarius|date=|accessdate=2017-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places of worship in the City of Leeds]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|St. Ricarius Church, Aberford}}\n*[https://www.achurchnearyou.com/aberford-st-ricarius/ St Ricarius' Church, Aberford]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aberford, St. Ricarius' Church}}\n[[Category:Churches in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Listed buildings in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Anglican Diocese of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Church of England church buildings in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed churches in West Yorkshire]]\n", "name_user": "Blythwood", "label": "safe", "comment": "Put coordinates parameter back", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Ricarius_Church,_Aberford"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Munford", "text_new": "{{short description|1865 battle in Munford, Alabama}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict = Battle of Munford\n|width = 330px\n|partof = the [[American Civil War]]\n|date = April 23, 1865\n|place = [[Munford, Alabama]]\n|result = [[United States|Union]] victory \n|combatant1 = {{flagicon|USA|1863}} United States ([[Union (American Civil War)|Union]])\n|combatant2  = {{flagicon|CSA}} [[Confederate States of America|CSA (Confederacy)]]\n|commander1  = Brig. Gen. [[John T. Croxton]]\n|commander2  = Brig. Gen. [[Benjamin J. Hill]]\n|units1= '''Croxton's Brigade''' <ref>[https://archive.org/details/08697590.3359.emory.edu/page/n675/mode/1up ''Dyer's Compendium'', Part 2, p.669]; [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077730103&view=1up&seq=424 ''War of the Rebellion, Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies'', Series I, Volume 49, Part 1, p.402.]</ref><br> 2nd Michigan Cavalry<br> 4th Kentucky Mtd. Infantry<br> 6th Kentucky Cavalry<br> 8th Iowa Cavalry\n|units2= '''Hill's Brigade''' <ref>Keenan, Jerry, ''Wilson's Cavalry Corps: Union Campaigns in the Western Theatre, October 1864 through Spring 1865'' (1998), p.209</ref><ref>General B.J. Hill (May 1865): \"I received authority from the Secretary of War of the Confederate States, approved by the House of Representatives and Senate, to raise a new brigade in North Alabama and North Georgia of mounted men. I have made my headquarters at Blue Mountain and Jacksonville, Ala., for the past three months, and have succeeded in organizing two small regiments, about one-half of whom were killed, captured, or deserted during the two late raids of Generals Wilson and Croxton through Alabama.\" [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077743023&view=1up&seq=711 ''War of the Rebellion, Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies'', Series I, Volume 49, Part 2, p.709.]</ref><br> Lowe's Alabama Cavalry <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Lnm6BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA103&dq=%22Lowe's+regiment+of+Hill's+brigade%22+%22reported+he+was+in+an+engagement+near+Oxford,+Alabama%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2gLGvoZjoAhVI4qwKHbYVCqEQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Lowe's%20regiment%20of%20Hill's%20brigade%22%20%22reported%20he%20was%20in%20an%20engagement%20near%20Oxford%2C%20Alabama%22&f=false Sterling, Robin, ''Blount County, Alabama Confederate Soldiers, Volume 3: Miscellaneous'', p.103.]</ref><br> Hays' Tennessee Cavalry <ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077723009&view=1up&seq=679 ''War of the Rebellion, Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies'', Series I, Volume 45, Part 2, p.677 (Cooper to Hill).]</ref><br> One section of artillery <ref> [https://archive.org/details/ahundredbattles00thatrich/page/243/mode/1up Thatcher, Marshall P., ''A Hundred Battles in the West'' (1884), p.243]; [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077730103&view=1up&seq=440 ''War of the Rebellion, Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies'', Series I, Volume 49, Part 1, p.418.]</ref>\n|strength1   = 1,500 <ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077730103&view=1up&seq=441 ibid., p.419]</ref>|strength2 = 500 <ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077730103&view=1up&seq=445 ibid, p.423]</ref><ref>Miller, Rex, ''Croxton's Raid'', p.79</ref>\n|casualties1 = '''Total: 11'''<br> Killed: 4<br> Wounded: unknown<br> Captured or Missing: 7\n|casualties2 = '''Total: 15'''<br> Killed: 1<br> Wounded: unknown<br> Captured: 14 <ref>Names appearing on a \"List of Prisoners of War captured by 1st Division Cavalry Corps, Military Division of the Mississippi\" (Register No. 63) at Munford, Ala., April 23, 1865, National Archives' Compiled Service Records of Confederate Soldiers.</ref>\n|notes = The 2nd Michigan Cavalry (the advance regiment of the brigade) lost two men killed, five missing and two captured in the charge through Munford.<ref>Miller, Rex, ''Croxton's Raid'', p.81;  Thatcher, Marshall P., ''A Hundred Battles in the West'' (1884), Roster;  ''Record of Service of Michigan Volunteers in the Civil War, 1861-1865'', Volume 32.</ref>  In rearguard actions, the 8th Iowa Cavalry lost two men killed.<ref>\"The Eighth was unfortunately in the rear, and had only a few skirmishes, in which, however, Wright, of Company E, and Standard, of Company K, were killed.\" ''Roster and Record of Iowa Soldiers in the War of the Rebellion'', Vol. 4 (1910), p. 1519.</ref>\n|campaignbox =\n}}\n[[File:Battle of Munford Historical Marker.jpg|thumb|300px|Battle of Munford historical marker.]]\n[[File:Monument to Lieutenant Andrew Jackson \u201cJack\u201d Buttram.jpg|thumb|300px|Monument to the last Confederate soldier killed east of the Mississippi.]]\n\nThe '''Battle of Munford''' took place in [[Munford, Alabama]], on Sunday, April 23, 1865, during the raid through the state by 1,500 [[Union Army]] cavalrymen under General [[John T. Croxton]], part of the force participating in [[Wilson's Raid]]. The Battle of Munford and a minor action at Hendersonville, North Carolina on the same day were the last battles of the [[American Civil War]] in the [[Eastern Theater of the American Civil War]] (east of the [[Mississippi River]]).\n\nThe [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] soldiers in the battle were described as convalescents, home guards, and pardoned deserters, while the Union cavalry was a veteran force armed with 7-shot [[Spencer repeating rifle|Spencer repeating carbines]]. The Confederate forces were commanded by General [[Benjamin Jefferson Hill]]. Confederate Lieutenant [[Lewis E. Parsons]] had two cannons which fired several rounds before they were overrun. The Union troops won the brief battle. Parsons was appointed provisional governor of Alabama in June after the war's end.\n\nThe Union and Confederate soldiers killed that day are described by author Rex Miller as the last to die in open combat by contending military forces.<ref>Miller, Rex, ''Croxton's Raid'', pp.80-81</ref>\n\n{{quote\n|THE LAST BATTLE.\n\nNumerous battles have been written up as \"the last fight of the rebellion.\" Without disputing in regard to the matter it is a fact, not generally known, that a battalion (the saber battalion) of the Second Michigan cavalry, under brevet Major Whittemore, charged the force under General Hill, near Talladega, Alabama, on the 23d of April, 1865, and was supported by the regiment and brigade, scattering the entire Confederate force and capturing the artillery, and many prisoners. This was fourteen days after the surrender at Appomattox, and therefore quite late enough after a cessation of hostilities. The next day the country was filled with small parties returning home\u2014a sadly broken down people.\n\n-Captain Marshall P. Thatcher, Second Michigan Cavalry <ref>[https://archive.org/details/ahundredbattles00thatrich/page/416/mode/1up Thatcher, Marshall P., ''A Hundred Battles in the West'' (1884), p.416]</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Alabama in the Civil War}}\n\n{{coord|33.533494|-85.954242|type:adm3rd_globe:earth_region:US-AL|display=title}} <!-- source: [[Munford, Alabama]] -->\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munford}}\n[[Category:Battles of the Western Theater of the American Civil War|Munford]]\n[[Category:Union victories of the American Civil War|Munford]]\n[[Category:1865 in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Battles of the American Civil War in Alabama|Munford]]\n[[Category:Talladega County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:History of Alabama]]\n[[Category:1865 in Alabama]]\n[[Category:April 1865 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1865 battle in Munford, Alabama}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict = Battle of Munford\n|width = 330px\n|partof = the [[American Civil War]]\n|date = April 23, 1865\n|place = [[Munford, Alabama]]\n|result = [[United States|Union]] victory \n|combatant1 = {{flagicon|USA|1863}} United States ([[Union (American Civi